name.text: Derivative of the sine of a rational function

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution

In this question, we compute the derivative using a combination of the chain rule and the quotient rule.
Let's first look at {@quot@} and calculate its derivative as we need it for the chain rule.

Using the quotient rule we get that the derivative is,

\(\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx} \left( {@quot@} \right) = \frac{{@aa@} ({@denom@}) - ({@numer@})}{({@denom@})^2} = \frac{{@expand(denom*aa-numer)@}}{({@denom@})^2}\)

We now apply the chain rule as follows,

\(\displaystyle \begin{align*} f'(t) &= \frac{d}{dx} \left( {@quot@} \right) \cdot \cos \left( {@quot@} \right) \\ &= \frac{{@expand(denom*aa-numer)@}}{({@denom@})^2} \cdot \cos \left( {@quot@} \right) \\ &= \frac{{@expand(denom*aa-numer)*cos(quot)@}}{({@denom@})^2} \end{align*}\)
